init-checkconf /path/to/your.conf to check if your configuration is valid or not.
initctl start <service> to start the service
initctl stop <service> to stop the service
initctl restart <service> to restart the service
initctl status <service> to see the status your service, whether its stopped, running etc.
initctl reload-configuration is used after you created a new configuration to reload the configurations
initctl list to see the list of all registered services
initctl list | grep <service> to see if your service is registered or not


The important states are as follows:

    waiting: the initial state of processing
    starting: where a job is about to start
    pre-start: where the pre-start section is loaded
    spawned: where a script section is about to run
    post-start: where post-start operations take place
    running: where the job is fully operational
    pre-stop: where pre-stop operations take place
    stopping: where the job is being stopped
    killed: where the job is stopped
    post-stop: where post-stop operations take place - to clean up

Waiting -> Starting -> Security -> Pre-Start -> Spawned -> Post-Start -> Running -> Pre-Stop -> Stopping -> Killed  -> Post-Stop -

